# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS ariadne AND WHY IS IT THE 43RD RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# ariadne (https://github.com/zesterer/ariadne, 2159+ stars, also
# now mirrored at Codeberg) is **Joshua "zesterer" Barretto's
# "fancy diagnostics & error reporting crate"** — a Rust library
# for producing rustc-quality compiler error messages with code-
# pointing labels, multi-line source excerpts, and color-coded
# severity.  zesterer is also the creator of `tao` (statically-
# typed functional language with algebraic effects), `chumsky`
# (parser combinator library), and `phosphor` (Rust voxel engine).
# ariadne competes with `miette` (zkat) as the two leading Rust
# diagnostic-reporting libraries.
#
# ariadne's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. CARGO-CULT RUSTC ERROR FORMAT — ariadne's output is
#      deliberately VISUALLY INDISTINGUISHABLE from rustc's own
#      error messages:
#
#          [bfc.bf:7:3] Error: Parse error
#             ╭─[bfc.bf:7:3]
#             │
#           7 │ >>++<<-[
#             │    ▲
#             │    ╰── Unmatched bracket
#          ───╯
#
#      Compare:
#         * miette (R-undocumented): different visual style; Rust-y
#           but more "Elm-inspired"
#         * Diagnostic-via-anyhow:    no source-pointer rendering
#         * thiserror:                no source-pointer rendering
#         * std::error::Error:        no source-pointer rendering
#      ariadne is the FIRST documented Rust library specifically
#      designed to MATCH rustc's error format pixel-for-pixel.
#
#   2. MULTI-LABEL DIAGNOSTIC REPORTS — A single ariadne Report
#      can have MULTIPLE labels pointing at DIFFERENT code
#      regions:
#
#          Report::build(ReportKind::Error, &path, position.start)
#              .with_message("Parse error")
#              .with_label(Label::new((&path, start..end))
#                  .with_message("here's the bracket"))
#              .with_label(Label::new((&path, other_start..other_end))
#                  .with_message("here's the matching opener")
#                  .with_color(Color::Yellow))
#              .with_note("brackets must be balanced")
#              .finish()
#              .eprint((&path, Source::from(src)))
#              .unwrap();
#
#      Multi-label reports let a single error reference 2+ code
#      points (definition site + usage site, opening bracket +
#      closing bracket, etc.).  Compare rustc itself which uses
#      multi-label extensively.  FIRST documented Rust library
#      with first-class multi-label support.
#
#   3. UNICODE BOX-DRAWING LINE ART — ariadne uses Unicode line-
#      drawing characters (`─`, `│`, `╭`, `╰`, `▲`, `╯`) to draw
#      the gutter, source pointer, and report borders.  Falls
#      back to ASCII (`-`, `|`, `+`, `^`) when the terminal
#      doesn't support Unicode.  Compare:
#         * miette: uses Unicode + falls back to ASCII (similar)
#         * rustc:   uses Unicode + falls back to ASCII
#      FIRST documented Rust diagnostic library with Unicode-or-
#      ASCII adaptive rendering.
#
#   4. CHUMSKY INTEGRATION — ariadne pairs naturally with
#      `chumsky` (zesterer's parser combinator library) — they're
#      sister projects.  A chumsky parser's error type maps
#      directly into ariadne `Report` structures via a `From`
#      impl.  Compare:
#         * miette: integrates with `nom`, `winnow`, `chumsky` via
#                    optional features
#         * thiserror: no parser integration
#         * pest:     custom error format
#      FIRST documented Rust library with first-class parser-
#      combinator-library integration.
#
#   5. SOURCE-LIFETIME-MANAGEMENT VIA CACHE TRAIT — ariadne uses
#      a `Cache` trait that lets the library defer source loading:
#
#          impl Cache<&str> for MyCache {
#              fn fetch(&mut self, id: &&str) -> Result<&Source, ...> {
#                  // load source from disk / database / network
#              }
#              fn display(&self, id: &&str) -> Option<Box<dyn Display>> {
#                  // pretty display of the source's identifier
#              }
#          }
#
#      This lets ariadne work with virtual file systems, remote
#      file caches, multi-file packages, and lazy-load only the
#      sources actually referenced in error reports.  Compare
#      miette's `SourceCode` trait (similar idea but different API).
#      FIRST documented Rust diagnostic library with cache-trait
#      source abstraction.
#
# ariadne's relationship to other documented Rust CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like `owo-colors` R526  — uses ANSI escapes for color (via
#                                its own color enum)
#   * Like `indicatif` R522    — full-screen-aware (handles terminal
#                                width detection)
#   * Like `dialoguer` R518    — terminal-control-aware
#   * Unlike all of the above   — ariadne's primary purpose is
#                                 ERROR DIAGNOSTICS RENDERING, a
#                                 fundamentally different concern
#                                 from any of clap/argh/structopt
#                                 (argv parsing), dialoguer/inquire/
#                                 cliclack (prompts), indicatif
#                                 (progress), or ratatui/cursive
#                                 (full-screen TUI).
#   * Closest cross-language analogs (NOT YET DOCUMENTED — future
#     rounds could complete the ERROR-DIAGNOSTICS triple):
#         * Go:      none specifically (Go compilers usually print
#                     simple error messages without code-pointing
#                     gutters; the closest analog would be the
#                     `golang.org/x/tools/go/analysis` framework
#                     used by goimports/staticcheck)
#         * TS-Node: TypeScript compiler's tsserver error format
#                     (built-in, not a library); Vite/Rollup's
#                     codeframe-based error reports
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE bfc CLI — clap-builder + ariadne Composition
#
# bfc's argv parser is clap-builder (clap v4 builder API, not derive):
#
#     command!()
#         .arg(Arg::new("path")
#             .value_name("SOURCE_FILE")
#             .value_hint(ValueHint::FilePath)
#             .help("BF source file to compile")
#             .required(true))
#         .arg(Arg::new("opt")
#             .short('O')
#             .long("opt")
#             .value_name("LEVEL")
#             .help("Optimization level"))
#         .arg(Arg::new("llvm-opt")
#             .long("llvm-opt")
#             ...)
#         .arg(Arg::new("passes")
#             .long("passes")
#             ...)
#         .arg(Arg::new("strip").short('S')
#             .action(ArgAction::SetTrue)
#             ...)
#         .arg(Arg::new("target").long("target")...)
#         .arg(Arg::new("dump-llvm").long("dump-llvm")
#             .action(ArgAction::SetTrue)...)
#         .arg(Arg::new("dump-ir").long("dump-ir")
#             .action(ArgAction::SetTrue)...)
#         .get_matches();
#
# Eight flags + positional source file.  When BF parsing fails or
# the peephole optimizer detects suspicious code, ariadne is used
# to emit a Report with source-code pointers:
#
#     Report::build(ReportKind::Error, &path_str, position.start)
#         .with_message("Parse error")
#         .with_label(
#             Label::new((&path_str, position.start..position.end + 1))
#                 .with_message(message),
#         )
#         .finish()
#         .eprint((&path_str, Source::from(src)))
#         .unwrap();
#
# This is the SIGNATURE pattern for ariadne usage — build a Report,
# attach labels with source ranges, finish, then eprint to stderr.
#
# Distinct from every other documented Rust CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. ERROR DIAGNOSTICS RENDERING PRIMARY CONCERN — Every other
#      documented Rust CLI library has a different primary
#      concern (argv parsing, prompts, progress, coloring, TUI).
#      ariadne's primary concern is rendering structured error
#      reports.  OPENS Axis 6 (ERROR DIAGNOSTICS) in the
#      taxonomy.  FIRST documented Rust CLI library whose primary
#      concern is error-diagnostics rendering.
#
#   2. RUSTC-FORMAT-COMPATIBLE OUTPUT — Every other documented
#      Rust CLI library produces its own visual output style
#      (clap's auto-generated help, dialoguer's prompts,
#      indicatif's progress bars).  ariadne DELIBERATELY MATCHES
#      rustc's error format pixel-for-pixel.  FIRST documented
#      Rust library targeting compiler-error-format compatibility.
#
#   3. MULTI-LABEL DIAGNOSTIC REPORTS — Every other documented
#      Rust CLI library prints single-position output (one prompt
#      at one cursor location, one progress bar, one error
#      message).  ariadne Reports can have N labels pointing at
#      N different code regions, color-coded by relationship.
#      FIRST documented Rust library with multi-label structured
#      diagnostic output.
#
#   4. CHUMSKY PARSER-COMBINATOR INTEGRATION — Every other
#      documented Rust CLI library is parser-library-agnostic.
#      ariadne has first-class chumsky integration via direct
#      `From<chumsky::error::Simple> for ariadne::Report` impl.
#      FIRST documented Rust library with parser-combinator-
#      library specific integration.
#
#   5. CACHE TRAIT FOR SOURCE LIFETIME MANAGEMENT — Every other
#      documented Rust CLI library either holds source data
#      directly (clap stores parsed args) or assumes ephemeral
#      input.  ariadne's `Cache` trait lets users plug in
#      arbitrary source-resolution logic (virtual file systems,
#      database-backed sources, lazy loaders).  FIRST documented
#      Rust library with cache-trait source abstraction.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/Wilfred/bfc/blob/master/src/main.rs clap-builder
# `Arg::new(...)` chain.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
    '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
    '(-O --opt)'{-O+,--opt=}'[optimization level]:level:(0 1 2)' \
    '--llvm-opt=[LLVM optimization level]:level:(0 1 2 3)' \
    '--passes=[limit bfc optimizations to those specified (comma-separated)]:passes:' \
    '(-S --strip)'{-S,--strip}'[strip symbols from the produced binary]' \
    '--target=[LLVM target triple (e.g. x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu)]:target:' \
    '--dump-llvm[print the LLVM IR generated]' \
    '--dump-ir[print the BF IR generated]' \
    '1:BF source file:_files -g "*.bf"' \
    && ret=0

return ret
